[simple-chatbot] response {
  lessonCode: '202-2B',
  lessonStepIndex: 1,
  lessonSectionPhase: 'teach',
  reply: 'In the electrical trade, measuring current and voltage is something you will do almost every day. It is vital to distinguish between the two so you can pick the right tool and setting for the job.\n' +
    '\n' +
    'Think of current as the actual flow of electricity moving through a conductor. we measure this flow in Amperes, often just called Amps. To get an accurate reading, we use an Ammeter. This instrument must be connected so that the electricity flows directly through the device itself.\n' +
    '\n' +
    'Voltage, on the other hand, is the electrical potential difference—you can think of it as the "pressure" pushing the electricity through the circuit. This is measured in Volts. To find this value, we use a Voltmeter. Instead of the current flowing through the meter, the Voltmeter is used to measure the difference between two specific points. You must ensure you’ve selected the correct function, as a single meter cannot measure both flow and pressure simultaneously without adjustment.\n' +
    '\n' +
    '1. Which specific instrument is used to measure the flow of electrical current in a circuit?\n' +
    '2. Which instrument is used to measure the electrical potential difference between two points?\n' +
    '3. What is the specific SI unit measured by an ammeter?',
  replyLength: 1215,
  finishReason: 'STOP',
  usageMetadata: {
    candidatesTokenCount: 246,
    promptTokenCount: 663,
    totalTokenCount: 1603
  }
}
