  reply: 'In this scenario, we are fault-finding an electric heater that has stopped working. We need to determine if power is reaching the heater and if the component itself is faulty.\n' +
    '\n' +
    '**Step 1: Check for electrical pressure**\n' +
    'First, we need to verify if there is electrical pressure (potential difference) reaching the heater terminals. This quantity is measured in **Volts**. To do this, you select a **Voltmeter**.\n' +
    '\n' +
    '**Step 2: Check the heating element**\n' +
    'Next, we want to see if the internal element is broken by measuring its opposition to current flow. This quantity is **Resistance**, measured in **Ohms**. To perform this check, you select an **Ohmmeter**.\n' +
    '\n' +
    '**Step 3: Ensure circuit safety**\n' +
    'Before using your Ohmmeter, you must confirm the circuit is fully isolated and "dead." Testing resistance on a live circuit will result in false readings and will likely damage your instrument.\n' +
    '\n' +
    '**Final Result:**\n' +
    'You use a **Voltmeter** to check for incoming supply and an **Ohmmeter** to test the element’s integrity.\n' +
    '\n' +
    '**Takeaway:**\n' +
    'Always match your instrument to the SI unit (Volts to Voltmeter, Ohms to Ohmmeter) and only ever measure resistance on dead circuits.\n' +
