  lessonCode: '202-2B',
  lessonStepIndex: 1,
  lessonSectionPhase: 'teach',
  reply: 'Welcome to the start of our session on measuring electrical quantities. To work safely and accurately on site, you need to be able to identify the correct tools for the job.\n' +
    '\n' +
    'First, we have current, which is the actual flow of electricity through a circuit. We measure this in Amperes (often shortened to Amps) using an instrument called an ammeter. Because we are measuring flow, the ammeter is connected so that the current passes through the device.\n' +
    '\n' +
    'Next, we have voltage. Think of this as the electrical "pressure" or the potential difference between two points. We measure this in Volts using a voltmeter. Unlike measuring current, a voltmeter is used to measure across two points in the circuit.\n' +
    '\n' +
    'A common mistake is assuming a single meter setting covers everything. You must specifically select the right tool or function for either flow or pressure to get an accurate reading and keep your equipment safe.\n' +
    '\n' +
    '1. Which specific instrument is used to measure the flow of electrical current in a circuit?\n' +
    '2. Which instrument is used to measure the electrical potential difference between two points?\n' +
    '3. What is the specific SI unit measured by an ammeter?',
