[simple-chatbot] response {
  lessonCode: '202-2B',
  lessonStepIndex: 1,
  lessonSectionPhase: 'teach',
  reply: 'When we start testing circuits, the two most common things we measure are current and voltage. Think of current as the actual flow of electricity moving through a conductor. We measure this flow in Amperes, often shortened to Amps, using an instrument called an ammeter. Because we are measuring the flow itself, an ammeter must be connected so that the current passes through the meter.\n' +
    '\n' +
    'Voltage, on the other hand, is the electrical pressure or potential difference that pushes the current along. We measure this in Volts using a voltmeter. Unlike measuring flow, we measure voltage across two different points in a circuit to see the difference between them.\n' +
    '\n' +
    'It is vital to select the correct instrument and setting for the job. A common mistake for beginners is thinking one simple setting handles both, but an ammeter and a voltmeter perform very different functions based on whether you are looking for electrical flow or electrical pressure.\n' +
    '\n' +
    '1. Which specific instrument is used to measure the flow of electrical current in a circuit?\n' +
    '2. Which instrument is used to measure the electrical potential difference between two points?\n' +
    '3. What is the specific SI unit measured by an ammeter?',
  replyLength: 1194,
  finishReason: 'STOP',
  usageMetadata: {
    candidatesTokenCount: 232,
    promptTokenCount: 695,
    totalTokenCount: 1546
  }
}
