  reply: 'To kick things off with measuring electrical quantities, we need to look at the two most fundamental measurements you will take on-site: current and voltage. Think of current as the actual flow of electricity through a conductor. To measure this flow, we use an ammeter, and the reading is given in Amperes, or Amps for short. Because we are measuring flow, the meter has to be connected so the current passes directly through the device.\n' +
    '\n' +
    'On the other hand, we have voltage, which is the electrical potential difference—essentially the "pressure" pushing the charge. For this, we use a voltmeter to get a reading in Volts. Unlike current, voltage is measured by placing the meter probes across two different points in the circuit to see the difference between them. It is vital to select the right tool and setting, as confusing flow with pressure is a common mistake that leads to incorrect readings.\n' +
    '\n' +
    '1. Which specific instrument is used to measure the flow of electrical current in a circuit?\n' +
    '2. Which instrument is used to measure the electrical potential difference between two points?\n' +
