[simple-chatbot] response {
  lessonCode: '202-2B',
  lessonStepIndex: 1,
  lessonSectionPhase: 'teach',
  reply: 'To understand how a circuit is performing, we need to distinguish between electrical flow and electrical pressure. Current represents the flow of electricity, and we measure this in Amperes (or Amps) using an instrument called an ammeter. Because an ammeter measures flow, it has to be connected so that the current passes through the device itself.\n' +
    '\n' +
    'On the other hand, voltage represents the electrical potential difference, which you can think of as the pressure between two points. We measure this in Volts using a voltmeter. Unlike an ammeter, a voltmeter is placed across two points to measure the difference between them. A common mistake for beginners is assuming one meter setting handles everything, but you must specifically select the right tool or setting for what you are measuring. Identifying whether you are checking for flow or pressure is the first step before you ever touch the probes to a circuit.\n' +
    '\n' +
    '1. Which specific instrument is used to measure the flow of electrical current in a circuit?\n' +
    '2. Which instrument is used to measure the electrical potential difference between two points?\n' +
    '3. What is the specific SI unit measured by an ammeter?',
  replyLength: 1163,
  finishReason: 'STOP',
  usageMetadata: {
    candidatesTokenCount: 224,
    promptTokenCount: 812,
    totalTokenCount: 1685
  }
}
