  reply: 'In this scenario, we’re looking at a heater that’s stopped working. We need to figure out which tools to use to find the fault.\n' +
    '\n' +
    'First, you need to check if there is "electrical pressure" reaching the heater. In technical terms, this is the potential difference. Since potential difference is measured in Volts, you select a Voltmeter for this part of the task.\n' +
    '\n' +
    `Next, if the power is reaching the unit but it's still not heating up, you need to check the heating element itself. You’re looking for the "opposition to current flow" to see if the element is broken inside. This quantity is Resistance, measured in Ohms, so you’ll need to use an Ohmmeter.\n` +
    '\n' +
    'There is a vital safety step here: before you use the Ohmmeter to check that element, the circuit must be fully isolated and proved dead. If you try to measure resistance on a live circuit, you’ll get a false reading and you’ll likely damage your meter.\n' +
    '\n' +
    'The main takeaway here is to always match your instrument to the SI unit of the quantity you’re testing—Volts to Voltmeter, Ohms to Ohmmeter—and never test resistance on a live circuit.\n' +
    '\n' +
    'Does that step-by-step process make sense, and are you ready to try a scenario yourself?',
  replyLength: 1185,
  finishReason: 'STOP',
