  reply: "Let's walk through this heater fault.\n" +
    '\n' +
    'First, we need to see if there is any electrical pressure reaching the heater. In technical terms, we are looking for the potential difference. Because the unit of measurement is Volts, you’ll need to select a Voltmeter for this part of the job.\n' +
    '\n' +
    "Second, if the power is reaching the unit but it's still not working, we need to check the heating element itself. We do this by measuring its opposition to current flow. This quantity is Resistance, measured in Ohms, so you’ll need an Ohmmeter.\n" +
    '\n' +
    "Crucially, before you use that Ohmmeter, you have to make sure the circuit is fully isolated and dead. If you try to measure resistance on a live circuit, you'll likely damage your meter and get a completely wrong reading.\n" +
    '\n' +
    'The final result is using a Voltmeter for the supply check and an Ohmmeter for the element check. The key takeaway is to always match your tool to the SI unit (Volts to Voltmeter, Ohms to Ohmmeter) and only measure resistance on dead circuits.\n' +
    '\n' +
    'Does that step-by-step process make sense to you, and are you ready to try a similar example?',
  replyLength: 1095,
  finishReason: 'STOP',
